00:10:07.020 --> 00:10:11.635
Now, what is a typographic scale?

00:10:11.635 --> 00:10:14.950
Well, the easiest way to explain is to show you.

00:10:14.950 --> 00:10:19.570
Here we have a website that I use all the time it's called types-cale.com,

00:10:19.570 --> 00:10:25.000
and here what you do is basically you set your base font size.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:29.770
You select a scale and that will give you a list of

00:10:29.770 --> 00:10:35.335
font sizes that you need to use to create this harmonious scale.

00:10:35.335 --> 00:10:39.925
If I were to change the ratio here,

00:10:39.925 --> 00:10:43.195
you will see that the scale changes as well.

00:10:43.195 --> 00:10:44.470
By using this tool,

00:10:44.470 --> 00:10:45.730
you can say, "Okay,

00:10:45.730 --> 00:10:49.015
this is what I'm going to use for heading one,

00:10:49.015 --> 00:10:54.040
heading two, three, four, five and six.

00:10:54.040 --> 00:10:57.205
This is what I use for smaller text.

00:10:57.205 --> 00:10:59.650
By using this tool,

00:10:59.650 --> 00:11:05.500
I make sure that my typography is always spot on because without it,

00:11:05.500 --> 00:11:12.430
you don't really know what kind of font sizes to use.

00:11:12.430 --> 00:11:14.725
I mean, you start with,

00:11:14.725 --> 00:11:19.210
let's say the base font size for the body text,

00:11:19.210 --> 00:11:21.490
which is usually 16 pixels.

00:11:21.490 --> 00:11:24.070
But what about after that?

00:11:24.070 --> 00:11:29.145
What do you use for the H1 or the H3?

00:11:29.145 --> 00:11:30.780
Do you use 20 pixels,

00:11:30.780 --> 00:11:32.700
or do you use 21 pixels?

00:11:32.700 --> 00:11:37.280
Or maybe you use whatever you think looks best?

00:11:37.280 --> 00:11:45.595
That can work but having a tool like this that tells you exactly what kind of,

00:11:45.595 --> 00:11:51.970
or what font sizes to use based on a scale is critical.

00:11:51.970 --> 00:11:55.405
The way this works is actually very simple.

00:11:55.405 --> 00:12:01.825
Let me open a calculator and explain the principle behind this.

00:12:01.825 --> 00:12:06.805
Type scale base works based on a ratio.

00:12:06.805 --> 00:12:09.340
We start with the base value,

00:12:09.340 --> 00:12:11.650
which is 16 pixels.

00:12:11.650 --> 00:12:15.280
That base value, we multiply by the scale,

00:12:15.280 --> 00:12:20.435
which in our case is 1.414,

00:12:20.435 --> 00:12:26.205
and that gives us the result, 22.624.

00:12:26.205 --> 00:12:28.620
Now for the next item on the scale,

00:12:28.620 --> 00:12:35.380
we take that value, 22.624 or 22.62.

00:12:35.380 --> 00:12:39.850
We can use two decimal places and we divide it,

00:12:39.850 --> 00:12:42.220
or we multiply it with the same ratio,

00:12:42.220 --> 00:12:48.280
1.414 and that will give us the next value.

00:12:48.280 --> 00:12:54.160
In our case, I actually used the wrong separator here.

00:12:54.160 --> 00:13:00.190
In our case it's 31.98 and you do that over and over and over

00:13:00.190 --> 00:13:06.880
again until you get all the values for the rest of your text elements.

00:13:06.880 --> 00:13:11.020
Now, the advantage of using a tool like

00:13:11.020 --> 00:13:15.010
Type Scale is that you don't have to make these calculations manually.

00:13:15.010 --> 00:13:21.340
It does it for you, and it does it in M's as well as in pixels.

00:13:21.340 --> 00:13:23.424
Now because I'm using Figma,

00:13:23.424 --> 00:13:27.640
I have a handy plugin that generates type scales

00:13:27.640 --> 00:13:31.840
for me and that plugin is called Font Scale.

00:13:31.840 --> 00:13:33.460
If you want to install it,

00:13:33.460 --> 00:13:36.175
you simply need to go to Plugins,

00:13:36.175 --> 00:13:42.940
Manage Plugin, and then search for Font Scale and install it.

00:13:42.940 --> 00:13:44.950
It's really, really simple.

00:13:44.950 --> 00:13:47.290
Now to use this Plugin,

00:13:47.290 --> 00:13:49.420
you enter the base font sizes,

00:13:49.420 --> 00:13:54.910
in my case is going to be 18 and choose the scale factor in my case

00:13:54.910 --> 00:14:01.330
is going to be major third and then, generate layers.

00:14:01.330 --> 00:14:07.945
That generated these layers and it can actually paste them in here.

00:14:07.945 --> 00:14:17.035
As you can see, that gives you text elements that have the correct font sizes.

00:14:17.035 --> 00:14:20.950
It's exactly the same as going here and saying, "Okay,

00:14:20.950 --> 00:14:26.650
I want to use 18 pixels and 1.250 or major third."

